				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\tau $$\end{document} decays into an electron or a muon, are also included. Several SM processes have the same final-state topology and are considered as background to the FCNC analysis. The main backgrounds are V+jets production (especially in association with heavy quarks), where V denotes a W or a Z boson, SM top-quark production, diboson production, and multi-jet production via QCD processes. The studied process can be differentiated from SM single top-quark production, which is usually accompanied by additional jets. Furthermore, FCNC production has kinematic differences from the background processes, such as lower transverse momenta of the top quark.

The ATLAS detector [34] is a multipurpose collider detector built from a set of sub-detectors, which cover almost the full solid angle around the interaction point.2 It is composed of an inner tracking detector (ID) close to the interaction point surrounded by a superconducting solenoid providing a 2T axial magnetic field, electromagnetic and hadronic calorimeters, and a muon spectrometer (MS). The ID consists of a silicon pixel detector, a silicon microstrip detector providing tracking information within pseudorapidity |η|<2.5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$|\eta | < 2.5$$\end{document}, and a straw-tube transition radiation tracker that covers |η|<2.0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$|\eta | < 2.0$$\end{document}. The central electromagnetic calorimeter is a lead and liquid-argon (LAr) sampling calorimeter with high granularity, and is divided into a barrel region that covers |η|<1.475\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
